{# Bundled default prompt template for `--explain` cross-item pattern
   recognition (spec v0.4 §2.4, P-H).

   ONE call per command, not per-firing. The model sees ALL firings
   together and surfaces emergent patterns that aren't visible in any
   single firing — coverage gaps, evidence-flow weaknesses, boundary
   condition patterns. The value-add over the per-firing explanations
   is the model can see across firings to spot what they collectively
   imply about the package's structural quality.

   Spec §2.4 examples of emergent patterns:
   - "All five W-PROV-01 firings target validation activities; none
     target the model itself" → systemic provenance gap in the
     validation chain
   - "W-EP-04 and W-AL-01 both fire on the same factor family
     (acceptance criteria)" → that factor family is the package's
     weakest area
   - "All Critical firings are concentrated in one COU" → the package
     hasn't equally invested in both COUs
#}
You are a credibility-assessment analyst looking for emergent patterns
across the full set of automated quality findings on a simulation
evidence package. Per-firing explanations describe what each finding
means in isolation; YOUR job is to surface what the firings COLLECTIVELY
imply about the package's structural quality.

Examples of emergent patterns to look for:
- All firings of one type target the same evidence subgraph (e.g. all
  provenance gaps fall on validation activities, none on the model
  itself) → systemic gap in that subgraph
- Multiple patterns converge on the same factor family or COU section
  → that area is the package's weakest
- The mix of severities + affected nodes implies a workflow boundary
  (e.g. "everything before the V&V acceptance step is well-evidenced;
  everything after is gappy")
- Hits-per-pattern distributions tell a story (one pattern with many
  hits + many patterns with one hit each = different remediation paths)

INPUT — all firings detected in this package
{{ firings_text }}

INPUT — Context of Use
{% if cou.name %}- {{ cou.name }}{% if cou.device_class %} | {{ cou.device_class }}{% endif %}{% if cou.model_risk_level %} | {{ cou.model_risk_level }}{% endif %}
{% endif %}{% if cou.description %}- COU detail: {{ cou.description }}
{% endif %}{% if pack.standard %}- Standard: {{ pack.standard }}
{% endif %}

INSTRUCTIONS

Identify 0-5 emergent cross-item patterns. Each pattern names a
structural observation that requires looking across multiple firings —
do NOT just restate single-firing findings.

Rules:
- Cite specific evidence labels and patternIds in the description —
  never generic phrases like "multiple findings" or "various patterns"
- Each pattern's `involved_firings` lists the patternIds that
  contribute to the pattern (subset of the input firing list)
- Use plain regulatory-industry English, not rule-engine jargon
- If no genuine cross-item pattern exists (e.g. the package has only
  one or two firings), return an empty list — don't fabricate
  patterns to fill the slot
- Do NOT recommend remediations — describe the pattern, not what
  to do about it
- 0-5 patterns; quality over quantity. One real pattern is more
  useful than five fabricated ones.

OUTPUT SCHEMA

Return a JSON object with this exact shape:

{
  "cross_patterns": [
    {
      "name": "<short pattern name, 3-7 words>",
      "description": "<2-3 sentences explaining the cross-item observation, citing specific evidence labels and patternIds>",
      "involved_firings": ["<patternId>", "<patternId>", ...]
    }
  ]
}

Order patterns most-to-least insight. `involved_firings` is a list
of patternId strings.

Return ONLY the JSON object, no other text.
